Answer: The problem in your code is that you are trying to store the token in an array of size 1. When you do String[] word={tokens.nextToken()};, it only stores the last token in the array. You should use a list to store all the tokens and then print them in reverse order.

Here is the corrected code:

```java
import java.util.StringTokenizer;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Example {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("type something here");
        String sentence = input.nextLine();
        StringTokenizer tokens = new StringTokenizer(sentence);
        ArrayList<String> wordList = new ArrayList<String>();

        while (tokens.hasMoreTokens()) {
            wordList.add(tokens.nextToken());
        }

        for (int y = wordList.size() - 1; y >= 0; y--) {
            System.out.print(wordList.get(y) + " ");
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, I have used an ArrayList to store all the tokens. Then, I have printed them in reverse order using a for loop.

Explanation: The StringTokenizer class in Java is used to break a string into tokens. The tokens are obtained by splitting the string using the specified delimiters. In this code, the delimiters are the spaces. The tokens are stored in an ArrayList and then printed in reverse order.

API: StringTokenizer.nextToken() - This method returns the next token from this string tokenizer.
